The Minister of Humanitarian Affairs, Disaster Management and Social Development, Sadiya Farouq on Thursday said that the Federal Government spent over N6 billion on beneficiaries of the N-Power scheme on a monthly basis. Sadiya Farouq stated this during the flagging off of the N-Skills Phone Repair programme in Bauchi State. While flagging off the programme, Sadiya said the government was focused on its promise to lift 100 million Nigerians out of poverty in 10 years, adding that the government kept budgeting $1 billion yearly on the Social Investment Programme (SIP). According to her, the Smart Phone Repairs is used to pilot the N-Skills programme, under the N-Power non-graduate programme. She said, “The programme is designed to train, tool and transition marginalised unemployed youths into the labour market for gainful employment. “The ministry is working with carefully selected consulting firms to provide the N-Skills for 6,475 unemployed youths across the Federation.” She added that 16,820 residents of Bauchi have benefited from N-Power Batch A, B and C, while the ministry “is spending over N6.2 billion for the training, tooling and/or payment of monthly stipends of the Batch C beneficiaries.”